# Core Testing Philosophy

## 1. Testing Principle
All tests must validate observable behavior, not implementation details.

Tests define what the system does, not how it is implemented.

---

## 2. Test Structure Rule (AAA)
All tests must follow:

- Arrange: setup state
- Act: execute behavior
- Assert: verify outcome

---

## 3. Test Isolation Rule
- Each test must be independent
- No shared mutable state
- Tests must be order-independent

---

## 4. Unit vs Integration Definition

### Unit Tests
- Test logic in isolation
- External dependencies must be mocked or stubbed

### Integration Tests
- Test interaction between components or layers
- May use in-memory or test implementations
- Must avoid external production systems

---

## 5. BDD Discipline
- Each test must represent one behavior
- Use Given / When / Then when expressing scenarios
- Do not combine multiple behaviors in one test

---

## 6. Refactor Safety Rule
- Refactoring must not change observable behavior
- Tests must not be modified during refactor unless behavior changes